"""
Created on Tue Mar  5 07:01:52 2024

Equidistant Ray Segmentation Method

Variant of the method EBSI Proposed by Du et al. (2015). Stress wave tomography, 
BioResources 10(3), 3948-3962.

The segment lengths are comparable.


Data from Analysis of wave velocity patterns in black cherry trees and its 
effect on internal decay detection

Black cherry trees I (17-50)

https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0168169914000684


Table 3 shows the measured velocity data for sample 1-50. Fig. 9
illustrates the theoretical velocity model of the black cherry and
the measured velocity data under source point 1, and Fig. 10 shows
the tomogram of sample 1-50.

It can be seen from Table 3 that, from source point 1, the wave
velocities were 999 m/s (1-2), 1150 m/s (1-3), 1199 m/s (1-4),
1184 m/s (1-5), 1044 m/s (1-6), 764 m/s (1-7), 826 m/s (1-8),
1048 m/s (1-9), 1110 m/s (1-10), 1064 m/s (1-11), and 996 m/s
(1-12). From Fig. 9, it can be seen that the line velocities of 1-5,
1-6, 1-7, 1-8, and 1-9 deviated from the theoretical values
dramatically. The largest deviation was the line velocity for 1-7,
which represents the radial direction. 

Consequently, we can speculate that internal decay exists in the central 
area of the cross section, and the decay area is surrounded 
by the lines 1-5 and 1-9, which matches with the tomogram 
of sample 1-50 reasonably well as shown in Fig. 10.

@author: marik
"""

e = 0.8

def shifted_coordinates(s, epsilon=0.05):
    """Allows to shift the ray a bit. Useful when two rays in opposite direction should
    be both visible on tomogram. the value epsilon describes how much 
    to shift the ray in the direction perpendicular to the ray.
    """
    start = s.start_coordinates
    end = s.end_coordinates
    vect = end-start
    shift = vect/np.linalg.norm(vect)
    shift = np.array([-shift[1],shift[0]])*epsilon
    start = start + shift
    end = end + shift
    return np.array([[start[0],end[0]],[start[1],end[1]]]) 

t = tomo.Tomo (speeds=data_velocity, nx=41, ny=41, symmetric=True)

# Fix the velocities as described in EBSI
# Du et al. (2015). Stress wave tomography, BioResources 10(3), 3948-3962.
t.fix_velocity_EBSI()

# limits = {"speed_max":1550, "speed_min":500}

# Each ray will be divided at least once
max_length = min([i.length for i in t.rays])*0.5

x = np.linspace(-1.2,1.2,100)
y = np.linspace(-1.2,1.2,100)
xx,yy = np.meshgrid(x,y)

# Find length for segmentation
lengths = [ray.length for ray in t.rays]
dl = min(lengths)/2
# Do the ray segmentation
for ray in t.rays:
    seg = list(ray.segments)[0]
    length = np.linalg.norm(seg.start_coordinates - seg.end_coordinates)
    n = length//dl
    seg.split(int(n))


MAX = np.nanmax([i.speed for i in t.rays])
MIN = np.nanmin([i.speed for i in t.rays])

# Draw the segments on the ray from one node
fig,ax = plt.subplots()
node = t.nodes[2]
for ray in node.rays_from:
    for s in list(ray.segments):
        center = 0.5*(s.start_coordinates+s.end_coordinates)
        major = np.linalg.norm(s.start_coordinates - s.end_coordinates)
        minor = major * np.sqrt( 1 - e**2 )
        color = tomo.speed2color(s.speed,max=MAX, min=MIN)
        angle = 90 - np.degrees(np.arctan2(*(s.start_coordinates - s.end_coordinates)))
        ellipse = Ellipse(center, major, minor, facecolor=color, angle=angle)
        ax.add_patch(ellipse)
        ax.plot(*list(zip(s.start_coordinates,s.end_coordinates)), color=color)
